SIMPLE: renown
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Renown
<hw>Re*nown"</hw> <pr>(r?-noun")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>renom</ets>. See <er>Noun</er>, and cf. <er>Renown</er>,
<pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state of being much known and
talked of; exalted reputation derived from the extensive praise of great
achievements or accomplishments; fame; celebrity; -- always in a good
sense.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor envy we⟦br⟧
Thy great <qex>renown</qex>, nor grudge thy victory.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Report of nobleness or exploits; praise.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This famous duke of Milan,⟦br⟧
Of whom so often I have heard <qex>renown</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Renown</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Renown
<hw>Re*nown"</hw> <pr>(r?-noun")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>renommer</ets> to name again, celebrate, make famous; pref.
<ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>nommer</ets> to name, L. <ets>nominare</ets> ,
fr. <ets>nomen</ets> a name. See <er>Noun</er>.]</ety> <def>To make
famous; to give renown to.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For joy to hear me so <qex>renown</qex> his son.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The bard whom pilfered pastorals <qex>renown</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Renowned</ent>⟦br⟧
